s Serenade, Faulkner's Sanctuary, Thompson's Pop. 1280, and Himes's Blind Man with a Pistol--in conjunction with their treatment of bodily metaphors of smell, vision, and voice. In the process, Forter unearths a "generic unconscious" that reveals things Freud both discovered and sought to repress.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican fictionxMale authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCrime in literature. 0aCriminals in literature. 0aDetective and mystery stories, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aFantasy in literature. 0aMasculinity in literature. 0aMen in literature. 0aPsychoanalysis and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aViolence in literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081472690740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814728185423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814728185/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK